From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Wed, 24 Jun 2026 17:51:11 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] kati: keep -j out of $(MAKE); add parallel-conformance corpus
 gate + box tests
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Conformance fix: -j was being propagated into subkati_args, which feeds the
$(MAKE) variable, so a `$(MAKE) …` recipe under -jN echoed `make -jN …` —
diverging from GNU make, which keeps the job count out of $(MAKE) (it rides
MAKEFLAGS / the jobserver). Stop propagating -j into subkati_args; $(MAKE) is now
just the program name at any -j, matching make.

Cover it (and the whole parallel scheduler) in the corpus: KATI_CORPUS_PARALLEL=1
re-runs every case with rkati -j4 from the same initial state and asserts its
output equals the -j1 run (order-independent — recipes interleave under -j). With
the $(MAKE) fix this is 364/364 with NO -jN normalization, so it genuinely proves
$(MAKE) is job-count-independent. Combined with the serial pass (rkati -j1 ==
make), this establishes rkati -j4 == -j1 == make transitively. The pass is a hard
assertion when enabled.

Box tests: CASE 16 (`make -j2` recipes overlap, peak concurrency exactly 2,
bounded by the pool) and CASE 17 (dependency ordering respected under -j4 — a
target's recipe sees its prerequisite's output).

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
Claude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01XyA6FzC6QGgsrjEYEBJV46
